{
  "texts": [
    "Plug the upper bound on E θ∼ρ [r(θ)] from the second line into the first line to get:",
    "Just replace δ by δ/2 to get the statement of the theorem.",
    "As mentioned above, the rate 1/ √ n that we have obtained in many PAC-Bayes bounds seen so far is not always the tightest possible.",
    "Actually, this can be seen in Tolstikhin and Seldin's bound (Theorem 3.3): there, if E θ∼ρ [r(θ)] = 0 for some ρ, then the bound is actually in 1/n.",
    "It appears that rates in 1/n are possible in a more general setting, under an assumption often refered to as Bernstein assumption."
  ]
}